const schema = [
  {
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Free APIs Guide",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Person",
      "name": "SiliconBased Editorial"
    }
  },
  {
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [

      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best free weather API?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "OpenWeatherMap and Open-Meteo are widely considered the best free weather APIs, offering robust data with generous free tiers."
        }
      },

      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Open-Meteo require an API key?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No, Open-Meteo is an open-source weather API that does not require an API key for non-commercial use."
        }
      },

      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I get historical weather data for free?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, Visual Crossing and Open-Meteo both offer free access to historical weather data via their APIs."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];

export const meta = {
  title: "Best Free Weather APIs in 2026",
  description: "OpenWeatherMap, Open-Meteo, Visual Crossing.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};
---
<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title="Best Free Weather APIs in 2026" description="OpenWeatherMap, Open-Meteo, Visual Crossing." canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/free-weather-apis" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Best Free Weather APIs in 2026</h1>
      <p>OpenWeatherMap, Open-Meteo, Visual Crossing.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="article-body">

    <h2>Integrating Weather Data</h2>
    <p>Weather data is a crucial component for a wide variety of applications, from simple dashboard widgets to complex logistics and agricultural software. Fortunately, several robust APIs provide free access to current conditions, forecasts, and historical weather data.</p>

    <h3>1. OpenWeatherMap</h3>
    <p>OpenWeatherMap is perhaps the most well-known weather API among developers. It provides highly accurate weather data globally, aggregating data from tens of thousands of weather stations, radars, and satellites.</p>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Features:</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Current weather conditions.</li>
        <li>Hourly and daily forecasts.</li>
        <li>Air pollution and UV index data.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Free Tier Details:</strong> The free tier offers 1,000 API calls per day, which is more than sufficient for development, testing, and small-scale applications.</p>

    <h3>2. Open-Meteo</h3>
    <p>Open-Meteo stands out as a completely open-source weather API. It is designed for ease of use, requiring no API key for non-commercial use. It pulls data directly from national weather services like the DWD (Germany) and NOAA (USA), providing high-resolution local models.</p>
    <p>One of Open-Meteo's best features is its historical weather data archive, which is invaluable for data science projects and machine learning training sets.</p>
    <p><strong>Free Tier Details:</strong> Up to 10,000 API calls per day for non-commercial use, without requiring registration.</p>

    <h3>3. Visual Crossing</h3>
    <p>Visual Crossing specializes in historical weather data and advanced weather metrics. It is highly favored by data analysts and enterprises needing complex weather modeling.</p>
    <p>Their API can return data in various formats, including JSON and CSV, making it easy to import directly into data visualization tools or spreadsheet software.</p>
    <p><strong>Free Tier Details:</strong> The free tier allows 1,000 records per day, providing access to their extensive historical database and 15-day forecasts.</p>

    <h2>Best Practices for Weather APIs</h2>
    <p>When working with weather APIs, caching is essential. Weather conditions rarely change significantly minute-by-minute. By caching the API response for 10 to 30 minutes, you can drastically reduce your API calls and ensure you remain within the free tier limits while improving the response time of your application.</p>

    <p><em>Return to the <a href="/best-free-apis-2026">Best Free APIs 2026</a> overview.</em></p>
    <h2>Related Guides</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/free-maps-apis">Free Maps APIs</a></li>
      <li><a href="/free-image-apis">Free Image APIs</a></li>
    </ul>


    </div>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    console.log("Loaded Best Free Weather APIs in 2026");
  </script>
